## Context
The NCC epic (0012) was killed because "Paris didn't matter" oversold
the data. But the periodization question is real and the existing
analysis has genuine signal. A proper paper needs continuous divergence
methods — no clustering, no arbitrary k. Each method produces a time
series; convergence across independent channels is the robustness signal.

## Method panel (16 methods + 3 change point detectors)

All methods are continuous (one value per window/year). Parameters
(window size, kernel, functional form) are acceptable; the number of
clusters is not.

### Semantic — 5 methods (embedding-based)

| ID | Method | Principle | Parameters | Library | Reference |
|----|--------|-----------|------------|---------|-----------|
| S1 | MMD (Maximum Mean Discrepancy) | Kernel two-sample test between embedding distributions of consecutive windows | Kernel (RBF), bandwidth | `dcor` or custom with `scipy` | Gretton et al. (2012) JMLR |
| S2 | Energy distance | Distribution-free two-sample test based on inter-point distances. No kernel to choose. | None (Euclidean) | `scipy.stats.energy_distance` | Székely & Rizzo (2004) JSPI; (2013) Ann. Stat. |
| S3 | Sliced Wasserstein distance | Optimal transport approximated by random 1D projections | Number of projections | `pot.sliced_wasserstein_distance` | Bonneel et al. (2015) JMIV |
| S4 | Fréchet distance (FID) | Model each period as multivariate Gaussian, compute Fréchet distance | Gaussian assumption | `scipy` (mean + covariance) | Dowson & Landau (1982) JMVA |
| S5 | Procrustes alignment + residual rotation | Train word embeddings per period, align via orthogonal Procrustes, measure rotation magnitude | Vocabulary size, embedding dim | `scipy.linalg.orthogonal_procrustes` | Hamilton et al. (2016) ACL |

S1–S4 apply directly to document embeddings (BGE-M3 already computed).
S5 requires per-period word embeddings — captures term-level semantic
drift rather than document-level distributional shift.

### Lexical — 3 methods

| ID | Method | Principle | Parameters | Library | Reference |
|----|--------|-----------|------------|---------|-----------|
| L1 | JS divergence on term distributions | Jensen-Shannon between TF-IDF distributions of two windows. Independent of embeddings. | Vocabulary size, window | `scipy.spatial.distance.jensenshannon` | Lin (1991) IEEE Trans. IT |
| L2 | Novelty / Transience | KL(doc‖past) = novelty, KL(doc‖future) = transience. Aggregated per year. Peaks of non-resonant novelty signal breaks. | Past/future window | `scipy.stats.entropy` (base KL) | Barron et al. (2018) PNAS |
| L3 | Burst detection (Kleinberg) | Finite automaton on term frequencies. Detects acceleration without arbitrary threshold. Aggregate: count of terms in burst per year. | State transition cost | `pybursts` | Kleinberg (2003) KDD |

L1 = global lexical divergence. L2 = separates what is new from what
persists. L3 = identifies which specific terms carry the change.

### Citation graph — 8 methods

| ID | Method | Principle | Parameters | Library | Reference |
|----|--------|-----------|------------|---------|-----------|
| G1 | PageRank volatility | PageRank per time slice; Kendall τ displacement between consecutive slices. High displacement = authority restructuring. | Damping factor, slice width | `networkx.pagerank` + `scipy.stats.kendalltau` | Brin & Page (1998); Ghoshal & Barabási (2011) |
| G2 | Spectral gap of Laplacian | Gap between 1st and 2nd eigenvalue of normalized Laplacian. Narrowing gap → emerging community structure. | None | `networkx.laplacian_matrix` + `scipy.linalg.eigsh` | Chung (1997); Chi et al. (2007) |
| G3 | Bibliographic coupling age shift | For papers in year t, distribution of publication years of shared references. Shift = changing intellectual foundations. | Min coupling threshold | `networkx` + `numpy` | Kessler (1963); Klavans & Boyack (2017) |
| G4 | Cross-tradition citation ratio | Define traditions by seed papers (not clustering). Track fraction of citations crossing tradition boundaries. 0 = silos, 1 = integration. | Seed selection | `networkx` | Leydesdorff (2007) JASIST; Rafols & Meyer (2010) |
| G5 | Preferential attachment exponent drift | Estimate exponent α per time slice. α > 1 = growing concentration. Regime change in α = structural shift. | Estimation window | `scipy.optimize.curve_fit` | Barabási & Albert (1999) Science; Newman (2001) |
| G6 | Citation entropy | Shannon entropy of incoming citation distribution per year. Low entropy = concentration around few authorities. | None | `scipy.stats.entropy` | Larivière et al. (2009) JASIST |
| G7 | Disruption index CD | Measures whether a paper consolidates (citants cite its refs) or disrupts (citants ignore its refs). Aggregated per year as mean CD. | None | `networkx` + `numpy` | Funk & Owen-Smith (2017); Wu et al. (2019) Nature |
| G8 | Betweenness centrality dynamics | Mean/max betweenness centrality per time slice in co-citation network. Peaks signal pivotal papers bridging communities. | Slice width | `networkx.betweenness_centrality` | Freeman (1979); Chen (2006) JASIST |

### Change point detection layer (3 meta-methods)

Applied to all 16 time series above. Convergence across channels is
the robustness criterion.

| ID | Method | Principle | Library | Reference |
|----|--------|-----------|---------|-----------|
| CP1 | PELT | Exact segmentation in linear time. Multiple breaks, no need to fix their count. | `ruptures.Pelt` | Killick et al. (2012) JASA |
| CP2 | BOCPD | Bayesian online detection. Outputs break probability at each point — no binary decision. | `ruptures` or `bayesian_changepoint_detection` | Adams & MacKay (2007) |
| CP3 | Kernel CPD | CUSUM based on MMD. Suited to multivariate series. | `ruptures.KernelCPD` | Harchaoui et al. (2009) NIPS |

## Dependencies to add

```
pot>=0.9.0        # Sliced Wasserstein (S3)
dcor>=0.6.1       # MMD alternative (S1)
ruptures>=1.1.9   # PELT, BOCPD, Kernel CPD (CP1-CP3)
pybursts>=0.1.1   # Burst detection (L3)
```

Already available via scipy/networkx: S2, S4, S5, L1, L2, G1-G8.

## Additional requirements

- External validation on 2-3 known-break corpora from OpenAlex
  (COVID-19 in public health, AlexNet in AI/ML, 2008 financial crisis)
- Honest framing: Copenhagen was the dominant founding shift,
  mid-2010s saw real redistribution, core shows no break

## Not yet decomposed
This is a future epic. Decompose when it becomes the next priority.

## Exit criteria
Paper submitted to a bibliometrics venue (QSS, Scientometrics, or
similar). Validated on external cases. Honest about what the data shows.
